INSERT INTO `content_blocks` VALUES (254,220,1,'paragraph',NULL,'It is 2 a.m. Your wife wakes you up: the contractions have started, or her water has broken. In the next thirty minutes you may need to call the clinic, call a taxi, or, if something is wrong, call <strong>119</strong> for an ambulance. This chapter gives you every sentence you need for that half hour, in the order you will actually use them.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(255,220,2,'paragraph',NULL,'Two key words first: <strong>陣痛 (jintsuu)</strong> means \"labor pains / contractions,\" and <strong>破水 (hasui)</strong> means \"water breaking.\" Both are above N5 level, but they are the two most important words in this entire book. Hospital staff will use them constantly.','Two key words first: <strong>陣痛 (jintsuu)</strong> means \"labor pains / contractions,\" and <strong>破水 (hasui)</strong> means \"water breaking.\" Both are above N5 level, but they are the two most important words in this entire book. Hospital staff will use them constantly.','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(256,221,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(257,222,1,'scene',NULL,'2:00 a.m. Your wife wakes you.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(258,222,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(259,223,1,'scene',NULL,'A different possible beginning: the water breaks first.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(260,223,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(261,223,3,'note','Important','<p>If the water breaks, most Japanese hospitals want the mother to come in <strong>immediately</strong>, even without contractions, and usually by car or taxi, not walking. When you phone, say clearly: <span lang=\"ja\">破水しました</span> (<em>Hasui shimashita</em>, \"Her water broke\").</p>','<p>If the water breaks, most Japanese hospitals want the mother to come in <strong>immediately</strong>, even without contractions, and usually by car or taxi, not walking. When you phone, say clearly: <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>破水<rp>（</rp><rt>はすい</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby>しました</span> (<em>Hasui shimashita</em>, \"Her water broke\").</p>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(262,224,1,'scene',NULL,'Maternity hospitals have a 24-hour phone line. A nurse or midwife answers.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(263,224,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(264,225,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(265,225,2,'note','Jinpu Taxi · 陣痛タクシー','<p>Many Japanese cities have a <strong>陣痛タクシー (jintsuu takushii)</strong>, a \"labor taxi\" service. You register your address and hospital in advance; when you call, drivers already know where to go and carry waterproof seats. Register during pregnancy, it is free and removes all language stress on the big night.</p>','<p>Many Japanese cities have a <strong>陣痛タクシー (jintsuu takushii)</strong>, a \"labor taxi\" service. You register your address and hospital in advance; when you call, drivers already know where to go and carry waterproof seats. Register during pregnancy, it is free and removes all language stress on the big night.</p>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(266,226,1,'scene',NULL,'Use 119 only for a true emergency: heavy bleeding, unbearable pain, the baby coming very fast, or the mother unable to move.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(267,226,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(268,227,1,'scene',NULL,'While waiting for the taxi, the husband calls his wife\'s mother, checks the hospital bag, and they leave.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(269,227,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(270,228,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(271,229,1,'culture_note','Things Foreign Residents Should Know','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Call before you go.</strong> In Japan you never simply show up at a maternity hospital at night. Always phone the 24-hour line first; the midwife decides when you should come.</li>\n      <li><strong>119, not 110.</strong> 119 is fire and ambulance; 110 is police. Ambulances in Japan are free of charge, but they are for genuine emergencies only, a normal labor is usually a taxi trip, not an ambulance trip.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 母子手帳 is sacred.</strong> The Maternal and Child Health Handbook contains the whole pregnancy record. Hospital staff will ask for it before almost anything else. Keep it, the insurance card, and the hospital card together in one pouch by the door from week 34.</li>\n      <li><strong>Pack the bag by week 35.</strong> Japanese hospitals give a printed list (pajamas, towels, pads, cash). Many payments still require cash or a specific machine, so keep ¥20,000, 30,000 in the bag.</li>\n      <li><strong>Speak slowly, not loudly.</strong> If you are not understood, repeat the key noun: 「陣痛です」「破水です」. Single clear keywords work better than long sentences.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Call before you go.</strong> In Japan you never simply show up at a maternity hospital at night. Always phone the 24-hour line first; the midwife decides when you should come.</li>\n      <li><strong>119, not 110.</strong> 119 is fire and ambulance; 110 is police. Ambulances in Japan are free of charge, but they are for genuine emergencies only, a normal labor is usually a taxi trip, not an ambulance trip.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 母子手帳 is sacred.</strong> The Maternal and Child Health Handbook contains the whole pregnancy record. Hospital staff will ask for it before almost anything else. Keep it, the insurance card, and the hospital card together in one pouch by the door from week 34.</li>\n      <li><strong>Pack the bag by week 35.</strong> Japanese hospitals give a printed list (pajamas, towels, pads, cash). Many payments still require cash or a specific machine, so keep ¥20,000, 30,000 in the bag.</li>\n      <li><strong>Speak slowly, not loudly.</strong> If you are not understood, repeat the key noun: 「陣痛です」「破水です」. Single clear keywords work better than long sentences.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(272,230,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(273,231,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(274,232,1,'paragraph',NULL,'The taxi pulls up. It is the middle of the night, the main entrance is dark, and you need to find the <strong>night entrance</strong> or <strong>emergency entrance</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">夜間入口 / 救急入口</span>). You may need to speak to the taxi driver, a security guard, and the night receptionist, possibly while carrying two bags and supporting your wife. This chapter covers everything between the car door and the reception desk.','The taxi pulls up. It is the middle of the night, the main entrance is dark, and you need to find the <strong>night entrance</strong> or <strong>emergency entrance</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>夜間<rp>(</rp><rt>やかん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>入口<rp>(</rp><rt>いりぐち</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby> / <ruby>救急<rp>(</rp><rt>きゅうきゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>入口<rp>(</rp><rt>いりぐち</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>). You may need to speak to the taxi driver, a security guard, and the night receptionist, possibly while carrying two bags and supporting your wife. This chapter covers everything between the car door and the reception desk.','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(275,233,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(276,234,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(277,235,1,'scene',NULL,'The main doors are locked. A security guard is standing nearby.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(278,235,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(279,236,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(280,237,1,'scene',NULL,'If you drive your own car instead of taking a taxi.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(281,237,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(282,238,1,'scene',NULL,'The husband presses the intercom at the night entrance. A nurse answers, lets them in, and guides them.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(283,238,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(284,239,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(285,240,1,'culture_note','Hospital Etiquette on Arrival','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Shoes:</strong> Many smaller maternity clinics ask you to change into slippers at the entrance. Look for a shoe shelf (<span lang=\"ja\">下駄箱</span>, getabako) with rows of slippers. Big general hospitals usually let you keep shoes on.</li>\n      <li><strong>Masks:</strong> Hospitals commonly expect masks indoors. Keep two masks in the hospital bag. If you forget, reception often sells them for ¥50, 100.</li>\n      <li><strong>Quiet at night:</strong> Speak in a low voice in corridors, other mothers and newborns are sleeping. Phone calls are only allowed in designated areas (<span lang=\"ja\">携帯電話コーナー</span>).</li>\n      <li><strong>The intercom ritual:</strong> At night, everything goes through the intercom (インターホン). State your family name and one keyword: 「田中です。陣痛です。」 That is enough, staff will take over.</li>\n      <li><strong>Taxi payment:</strong> Pay quickly with IC card or exact cash if possible. It is normal and not rude to leave immediately; Japanese taxi doors open automatically, don\'t slam them.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Shoes:</strong> Many smaller maternity clinics ask you to change into slippers at the entrance. Look for a shoe shelf (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>下駄<rp>(</rp><rt>げた</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>箱<rp>(</rp><rt>ばこ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, getabako) with rows of slippers. Big general hospitals usually let you keep shoes on.</li>\n      <li><strong>Masks:</strong> Hospitals commonly expect masks indoors. Keep two masks in the hospital bag. If you forget, reception often sells them for ¥50, 100.</li>\n      <li><strong>Quiet at night:</strong> Speak in a low voice in corridors, other mothers and newborns are sleeping. Phone calls are only allowed in designated areas (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>携帯<rp>(</rp><rt>けいたい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>電話<rp>(</rp><rt>でんわ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>コーナー</span>).</li>\n      <li><strong>The intercom ritual:</strong> At night, everything goes through the intercom (インターホン). State your family name and one keyword: 「田中です。陣痛です。」 That is enough, staff will take over.</li>\n      <li><strong>Taxi payment:</strong> Pay quickly with IC card or exact cash if possible. It is normal and not rude to leave immediately; Japanese taxi doors open automatically, don\'t slam them.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(286,241,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(287,242,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(288,243,1,'paragraph',NULL,'At the reception desk (<span lang=\"ja\">受付</span>, <em>uketsuke</em>) you present your documents and explain why you have come. In Japan you will always be asked for four key items: the <strong>hospital card</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">診察券</span>), the <strong>health insurance card</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">保険証</span>), the <strong>Maternal and Child Health Handbook</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">母子手帳</span>), and, for foreign residents, often the <strong>residence card</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">在留カード</span>). This chapter drills every sentence and every document.','At the reception desk (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>受付<rp>(</rp><rt>うけつけ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>uketsuke</em>) you present your documents and explain why you have come. In Japan you will always be asked for four key items: the <strong>hospital card</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>診察券<rp>（</rp><rt>しんさつけん</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>), the <strong>health insurance card</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>保険証<rp>（</rp><rt>ほけんしょう</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>), the <strong>Maternal and Child Health Handbook</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>母子手帳<rp>（</rp><rt>ぼしてちょう</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>), and, for foreign residents, often the <strong>residence card</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>在留<rp>(</rp><rt>ざいりゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>カード</span>). This chapter drills every sentence and every document.','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(289,244,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(290,245,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(291,246,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(292,247,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(293,248,1,'scene',NULL,'The complete reception exchange, including every document a foreign resident is asked for.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(294,248,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(295,249,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(296,250,1,'culture_note','Documents & Reception Etiquette','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Hand documents with both hands.</strong> In Japan, cards and papers are passed and received with two hands, or with the right hand supported by the left. A small bow of the head as you hand over the 保険証 is normal and appreciated.</li>\n      <li><strong>The four documents, memorized:</strong> 診察券 (hospital card) · 保険証 (insurance card) · 母子手帳 (handbook) · 在留カード (residence card). Keep them clipped together. Reception asks for them in almost this order.</li>\n      <li><strong>「失礼ですが」 is not rude.</strong> When staff say <span lang=\"ja\">失礼ですが</span> (\"excuse me, but…\") before asking for your residence card, it is polite softening, not suspicion. All foreign residents are asked.</li>\n      <li><strong>Private vs. shared room.</strong> A 個室 (private room) costs extra per night (差額ベッド代, <em>sagaku beddo-dai</em>) and is not covered by insurance. A 大部屋 (shared room, usually 4 beds) is free under insurance. Decide in advance.</li>\n      <li><strong>Say your name humbly.</strong> Use <span lang=\"ja\">〜と申します</span> (<em>…to moushimasu</em>, \"my name is…\") rather than <span lang=\"ja\">〜です</span> at first contact, it is the polite standard in hospitals and offices.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Hand documents with both hands.</strong> In Japan, cards and papers are passed and received with two hands, or with the right hand supported by the left. A small bow of the head as you hand over the 保険証 is normal and appreciated.</li>\n      <li><strong>The four documents, memorized:</strong> 診察券 (hospital card) · 保険証 (insurance card) · 母子手帳 (handbook) · 在留カード (residence card). Keep them clipped together. Reception asks for them in almost this order.</li>\n      <li><strong>「失礼ですが」 is not rude.</strong> When staff say <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>失礼<rp>(</rp><rt>しつれい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ですが</span> (\"excuse me, but…\") before asking for your residence card, it is polite softening, not suspicion. All foreign residents are asked.</li>\n      <li><strong>Private vs. shared room.</strong> A 個室 (private room) costs extra per night (差額ベッド代, <em>sagaku beddo-dai</em>) and is not covered by insurance. A 大部屋 (shared room, usually 4 beds) is free under insurance. Decide in advance.</li>\n      <li><strong>Say your name humbly.</strong> Use <span lang=\"ja\">〜と<ruby>申<rp>(</rp><rt>もう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>します</span> (<em>…to moushimasu</em>, \"my name is…\") rather than <span lang=\"ja\">〜です</span> at first contact, it is the polite standard in hospitals and offices.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(297,251,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(298,252,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(299,253,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Admission (<span lang=\"ja\">入院</span>, <em>nyuuin</em>) means signing forms and answering medical-history questions. The staff will ask about allergies, previous pregnancies, the due date, and past illnesses. These questions come from the <span lang=\"ja\">問診票</span> (<em>monshinhyou</em>, \"medical questionnaire\"), the same form printed in your 母子手帳. This chapter gives you the words to answer clearly even when the questions come fast.','Admission (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>入院<rp>(</rp><rt>にゅういん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>nyuuin</em>) means signing forms and answering medical-history questions. The staff will ask about allergies, previous pregnancies, the due date, and past illnesses. These questions come from the <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>問診票<rp>（</rp><rt>もんしんひょう</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span> (<em>monshinhyou</em>, \"medical questionnaire\"), the same form printed in your 母子手帳. This chapter gives you the words to answer clearly even when the questions come fast.','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(300,254,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(301,255,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(302,256,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(303,257,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(304,258,1,'scene',NULL,'A nurse goes through the full admission questionnaire while the husband helps translate for his wife.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(305,258,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(306,259,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(307,260,1,'culture_note','Paperwork & Privacy in Japan','<ul>\n      <li><strong>The husband can sign.</strong> When the mother is in pain, the husband (as guarantor / 保証人, <em>hoshounin</em>) usually signs admission and consent forms. Bring your own <span lang=\"ja\">在留カード</span> and 印鑑 (<em>inkan</em>, personal seal) if you have one, some forms ask for a seal instead of a signature.</li>\n      <li><strong>Consent forms are real.</strong> The 同意書 for delivery, anesthesia, or a possible C-section (帝王切開, <em>teiou sekkai</em>) is legally meaningful. If you don\'t understand, say <span lang=\"ja\">「意味が分かりません。説明してください。」</span> (\"I don\'t understand the meaning. Please explain.\"), never sign blindly.</li>\n      <li><strong>State allergies loudly and early.</strong> Repeat drug allergies twice; write them in English capitals on the form too. Staff take 薬アレルギー (drug allergy) extremely seriously.</li>\n      <li><strong>Privacy is protected.</strong> Japanese hospitals will not share the mother\'s condition with anyone not listed as family or emergency contact. Make sure your name is on the 緊急連絡先 line.</li>\n      <li><strong>Keep every receipt.</strong> Admission generates paperwork you\'ll need later for the lump-sum childbirth grant (出産育児一時金) and insurance. Put all papers in one folder from day one.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>The husband can sign.</strong> When the mother is in pain, the husband (as guarantor / 保証人, <em>hoshounin</em>) usually signs admission and consent forms. Bring your own <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>在留<rp>(</rp><rt>ざいりゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>カード</span> and 印鑑 (<em>inkan</em>, personal seal) if you have one, some forms ask for a seal instead of a signature.</li>\n      <li><strong>Consent forms are real.</strong> The 同意書 for delivery, anesthesia, or a possible C-section (帝王切開, <em>teiou sekkai</em>) is legally meaningful. If you don\'t understand, say <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>意味<rp>(</rp><rt>いみ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>が<ruby>分<rp>(</rp><rt>わ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>かりません。<ruby>説明<rp>(</rp><rt>せつめい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>してください。」</span> (\"I don\'t understand the meaning. Please explain.\"), never sign blindly.</li>\n      <li><strong>State allergies loudly and early.</strong> Repeat drug allergies twice; write them in English capitals on the form too. Staff take 薬アレルギー (drug allergy) extremely seriously.</li>\n      <li><strong>Privacy is protected.</strong> Japanese hospitals will not share the mother\'s condition with anyone not listed as family or emergency contact. Make sure your name is on the 緊急連絡先 line.</li>\n      <li><strong>Keep every receipt.</strong> Admission generates paperwork you\'ll need later for the lump-sum childbirth grant (出産育児一時金) and insurance. Put all papers in one folder from day one.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(308,261,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(309,262,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(310,263,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Paperwork is done. A nurse takes you up to the room, either a <strong>private room</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">個室</span>) or a <strong>shared room</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">大部屋</span>). Your wife will change into a hospital gown (<span lang=\"ja\">着がえる</span>, <em>kigaeru</em>) and you\'ll unpack. You need to know your room number, where the toilet is, and where you, the husband, are allowed to be.','Paperwork is done. A nurse takes you up to the room, either a <strong>private room</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>個室<rp>(</rp><rt>こしつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>) or a <strong>shared room</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>大部屋<rp>(</rp><rt>おおべや</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>). Your wife will change into a hospital gown (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>着<rp>(</rp><rt>ちゃく</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>がえる</span>, <em>kigaeru</em>) and you\'ll unpack. You need to know your room number, where the toilet is, and where you, the husband, are allowed to be.','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(311,264,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(312,265,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(313,266,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(314,267,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(315,268,1,'scene',NULL,'The nurse explains the room: the nurse call, the bed, the rules, and whether the husband can stay.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(316,268,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(317,269,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(318,270,1,'culture_note','Room Etiquette in a Japanese Hospital','<ul>\n      <li><strong>遠慮 (enryo) is the enemy.</strong> Japanese politeness teaches you to hold back, but nurses will repeatedly say <span lang=\"ja\">「遠慮なく」</span> (\"without hesitation\"). They mean it. Press the nurse call when your wife needs help. It is not rude.</li>\n      <li><strong>Shared rooms have curtains, not walls.</strong> In a 大部屋, everything you say is heard by three other families. Speak softly. Husbands generally cannot sleep in a shared room, only in a 個室.</li>\n      <li><strong>Slippers indoors.</strong> Patients wear slippers or soft shoes in the room. Don\'t walk in outdoor shoes across a hospital room floor if slippers are provided.</li>\n      <li><strong>Phones:</strong> Set your phone to silent (<span lang=\"ja\">マナーモード</span>, \"manner mode\"). Calls in the room or corridor are often prohibited; use the designated phone corner.</li>\n      <li><strong>Valuables:</strong> Hospitals accept no responsibility for cash left in rooms. Use the locker (usually with a coin-return key) and keep only what you need.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>遠慮 (enryo) is the enemy.</strong> Japanese politeness teaches you to hold back, but nurses will repeatedly say <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>遠慮<rp>(</rp><rt>えんりょ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>なく」</span> (\"without hesitation\"). They mean it. Press the nurse call when your wife needs help. It is not rude.</li>\n      <li><strong>Shared rooms have curtains, not walls.</strong> In a 大部屋, everything you say is heard by three other families. Speak softly. Husbands generally cannot sleep in a shared room, only in a 個室.</li>\n      <li><strong>Slippers indoors.</strong> Patients wear slippers or soft shoes in the room. Don\'t walk in outdoor shoes across a hospital room floor if slippers are provided.</li>\n      <li><strong>Phones:</strong> Set your phone to silent (<span lang=\"ja\">マナーモード</span>, \"manner mode\"). Calls in the room or corridor are often prohibited; use the designated phone corner.</li>\n      <li><strong>Valuables:</strong> Hospitals accept no responsibility for cash left in rooms. Use the locker (usually with a coin-return key) and keep only what you need.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(319,271,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(320,272,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(321,273,1,'paragraph',NULL,'The nurse (<span lang=\"ja\">看護師</span>, <em>kangoshi</em>) now checks your wife\'s condition: pain level, contraction timing, blood pressure (<span lang=\"ja\">血圧測定</span>), temperature, and the baby\'s movements. She will also coach the breathing. Two phrases you will hear over and over in this hospital and in the delivery room: <strong>深呼吸してください</strong> (<em>shinkokyuu shite kudasai</em>, \"take a deep breath\") and <strong>力をぬいてください</strong> (<em>chikara o nuite kudasai</em>, \"relax / let the strength go\").','The nurse (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>看護<rp>(</rp><rt>かんご</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>師<rp>(</rp><rt>し</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>kangoshi</em>) now checks your wife\'s condition: pain level, contraction timing, blood pressure (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>血圧<rp>(</rp><rt>けつあつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>測定<rp>(</rp><rt>そくてい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>), temperature, and the baby\'s movements. She will also coach the breathing. Two phrases you will hear over and over in this hospital and in the delivery room: <strong>深呼吸してください</strong> (<em>shinkokyuu shite kudasai</em>, \"take a deep breath\") and <strong>力をぬいてください</strong> (<em>chikara o nuite kudasai</em>, \"relax / let the strength go\").','2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(322,274,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(323,275,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(324,276,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(325,277,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(326,278,1,'scene',NULL,'A strong contraction arrives. The nurse coaches; the husband learns how to help.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(327,278,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:34','2026-07-12 20:17:34'),(328,279,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(329,280,1,'culture_note','Nurses, Midwives, and Pain in Japan','<ul>\n      <li><strong>The midwife runs the birth.</strong> In Japan the <span lang=\"ja\">助産師</span> (<em>josanshi</em>, midwife), not the doctor, is usually with the mother the whole time. The doctor appears for examinations and the delivery itself. Direct your everyday questions to the midwife.</li>\n      <li><strong>Natural birth is the default.</strong> Epidurals (<span lang=\"ja\">無痛分娩</span>, <em>mutsuu bunben</em>) exist but are far less common than in the West, cost extra, and must usually be arranged months in advance. If you want one, ask at the very first prenatal visit, not on the night.</li>\n      <li><strong>「がんばって」 is the core word.</strong> Nurses will say <span lang=\"ja\">がんばってください</span> (\"do your best / hold on\") constantly. It is genuine encouragement, not pressure.</li>\n      <li><strong>Massage is welcome.</strong> Husbands are actively expected to rub the lower back (<span lang=\"ja\">腰をさする</span>) and press the hips during contractions. Ask the midwife to show you the spot, she will.</li>\n      <li><strong>Say when it hurts.</strong> Foreign patients often under-report pain out of politeness. Japanese staff cannot help what they don\'t hear. Teach your wife: <span lang=\"ja\">「痛いです」「がまんできません」</span> (\"It hurts\" / \"I can\'t bear it\").</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>The midwife runs the birth.</strong> In Japan the <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>助産師<rp>（</rp><rt>じょさんし</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span> (<em>josanshi</em>, midwife), not the doctor, is usually with the mother the whole time. The doctor appears for examinations and the delivery itself. Direct your everyday questions to the midwife.</li>\n      <li><strong>Natural birth is the default.</strong> Epidurals (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>無痛<rp>(</rp><rt>むつう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>分娩<rp>（</rp><rt>ぶんべん</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>, <em>mutsuu bunben</em>) exist but are far less common than in the West, cost extra, and must usually be arranged months in advance. If you want one, ask at the very first prenatal visit, not on the night.</li>\n      <li><strong>「がんばって」 is the core word.</strong> Nurses will say <span lang=\"ja\">がんばってください</span> (\"do your best / hold on\") constantly. It is genuine encouragement, not pressure.</li>\n      <li><strong>Massage is welcome.</strong> Husbands are actively expected to rub the lower back (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>腰<rp>(</rp><rt>こし</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>をさする</span>) and press the hips during contractions. Ask the midwife to show you the spot, she will.</li>\n      <li><strong>Say when it hurts.</strong> Foreign patients often under-report pain out of politeness. Japanese staff cannot help what they don\'t hear. Teach your wife: <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>痛<rp>(</rp><rt>いた</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>いです」「がまんできません」</span> (\"It hurts\" / \"I can\'t bear it\").</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(330,281,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(331,282,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(332,283,1,'paragraph',NULL,'The doctor comes to check how far labor has progressed. The key procedure is the <strong>内診</strong> (<em>naishin</em>, internal examination), the doctor checks the cervix (<span lang=\"ja\">子宮口</span>, <em>shikyuukou</em>) and how many centimeters it has opened. You will also hear <span lang=\"ja\">超音波検査</span> / <span lang=\"ja\">エコー</span> (ultrasound) and <span lang=\"ja\">胎児心音</span> (the baby\'s heartbeat).','The doctor comes to check how far labor has progressed. The key procedure is the <strong>内診</strong> (<em>naishin</em>, internal examination), the doctor checks the cervix (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>子宮<rp>(</rp><rt>しきゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>口<rp>(</rp><rt>ぐち</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>shikyuukou</em>) and how many centimeters it has opened. You will also hear <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>超<rp>(</rp><rt>ちょう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>音波<rp>(</rp><rt>おんぱ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>検査<rp>(</rp><rt>けんさ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> / <span lang=\"ja\">エコー</span> (ultrasound) and <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>胎児<rp>(</rp><rt>たいじ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>心音<rp>(</rp><rt>しんおん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> (the baby\'s heartbeat).','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(333,283,2,'note','Words you must know before the doctor speaks','<ul>\n      <li><strong>内診 (naishin)</strong>, internal exam. The doctor will say something like 「下から診ますね」 (\"I\'ll examine from below\"). Underwear comes off; the wife lies on the exam table (<span lang=\"ja\">診察台</span>).</li>\n      <li><strong>子宮口 (shikyuukou)</strong>, the cervix. Measured in centimeters: 全開 (<em>zenkai</em>, fully open) = 10 cm.</li>\n      <li><strong>エコー / 超音波検査 (ekoo / chouonpa kensa)</strong>, ultrasound.</li>\n      <li><strong>ノンストレステスト (non-sutoresu tesuto, NST)</strong>, a 40, 60 minute monitor of contractions and the baby\'s heart rate, with two belts on the belly.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>内診 (naishin)</strong>, internal exam. The doctor will say something like 「下から診ますね」 (\"I\'ll examine from below\"). Underwear comes off; the wife lies on the exam table (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>診察<rp>(</rp><rt>しんさつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>台<rp>(</rp><rt>だい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>).</li>\n      <li><strong>子宮口 (shikyuukou)</strong>, the cervix. Measured in centimeters: 全開 (<em>zenkai</em>, fully open) = 10 cm.</li>\n      <li><strong>エコー / 超音波検査 (ekoo / chouonpa kensa)</strong>, ultrasound.</li>\n      <li><strong>ノンストレステスト (non-sutoresu tesuto, NST)</strong>, a 40, 60 minute monitor of contractions and the baby\'s heart rate, with two belts on the belly.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(334,284,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(335,285,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(336,286,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(337,287,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(338,288,1,'scene',NULL,'The doctor explains the exam results and answers the husband\'s questions.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(339,288,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(340,289,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(341,290,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(342,291,1,'culture_note','Talking with Japanese Doctors','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Doctors are brief.</strong> Japanese doctors often give short explanations and don\'t expect many questions. This is not coldness, it\'s style. You are allowed to ask. Prepare 2, 3 questions in advance and ask them clearly.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ask for a slower repeat.</strong> The single most useful sentence in the hospital: <span lang=\"ja\">「すみません、もう一度ゆっくりお願いします。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Interpreters exist.</strong> Larger hospitals have a <span lang=\"ja\">医療通訳</span> (<em>iryou tsuuyaku</em>, medical interpreter) service, sometimes by tablet/video. Ask at the first prenatal visit: <span lang=\"ja\">「医療通訳はありますか。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Attendance at birth (立ち会い, tachiai)</strong> is common but must be arranged in advance, and some hospitals require the husband to have attended a prenatal class. Confirm the policy months before.</li>\n      <li><strong>Photos:</strong> Do not photograph or film during examinations without asking. In the delivery room, filming rules vary, ask first: <span lang=\"ja\">「写真を撮ってもいいですか。」</span></li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Doctors are brief.</strong> Japanese doctors often give short explanations and don\'t expect many questions. This is not coldness, it\'s style. You are allowed to ask. Prepare 2, 3 questions in advance and ask them clearly.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ask for a slower repeat.</strong> The single most useful sentence in the hospital: <span lang=\"ja\">「すみません、もう<ruby>一度<rp>(</rp><rt>いちど</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ゆっくりお<ruby>願<rp>(</rp><rt>ねが</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>いします。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Interpreters exist.</strong> Larger hospitals have a <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>医療<rp>(</rp><rt>いりょう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>通訳<rp>(</rp><rt>つうやく</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> (<em>iryou tsuuyaku</em>, medical interpreter) service, sometimes by tablet/video. Ask at the first prenatal visit: <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>医療<rp>(</rp><rt>いりょう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>通訳<rp>(</rp><rt>つうやく</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>はありますか。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Attendance at birth (立ち会い, tachiai)</strong> is common but must be arranged in advance, and some hospitals require the husband to have attended a prenatal class. Confirm the policy months before.</li>\n      <li><strong>Photos:</strong> Do not photograph or film during examinations without asking. In the delivery room, filming rules vary, ask first: <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>写真<rp>(</rp><rt>しゃしん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>を<ruby>撮<rp>(</rp><rt>と</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ってもいいですか。」</span></li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(343,292,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(344,293,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(345,294,1,'paragraph',NULL,'This is the long part, often 6 to 12 hours in the <span lang=\"ja\">陣痛室</span> (<em>jintsuushitsu</em>, labor room). Contractions get stronger and closer together. Your job as the husband is simple and enormous: <strong>be there, breathe with her, rub her back, and encourage her</strong>. This chapter is mostly encouragement (<span lang=\"ja\">はげまし</span>, <em>hagemashi</em>), the sentences you will say a hundred times tonight.','This is the long part, often 6 to 12 hours in the <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>陣痛<rp>（</rp><rt>じんつう</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby><ruby>室<rp>(</rp><rt>しつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> (<em>jintsuushitsu</em>, labor room). Contractions get stronger and closer together. Your job as the husband is simple and enormous: <strong>be there, breathe with her, rub her back, and encourage her</strong>. This chapter is mostly encouragement (<span lang=\"ja\">はげまし</span>, <em>hagemashi</em>), the sentences you will say a hundred times tonight.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(346,295,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(347,296,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(348,297,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(349,298,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(350,299,1,'scene',NULL,'3 a.m. Husband, wife, midwife, nurse, and doctor. Contractions are three minutes apart.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(351,299,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(352,300,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(353,301,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(354,302,1,'culture_note','Being a Husband in a Japanese Labor Room','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Presence is the job.</strong> Japanese midwives do not expect the husband to give medical opinions. They expect him to be calm, quiet, and physically helpful: water, ice, towel, back massage, hand to hold.</li>\n      <li><strong>Don\'t leave without saying so.</strong> If you step out, tell the midwife: <span lang=\"ja\">「ちょっと出ます。すぐ戻ります。」</span> (\"I\'m stepping out. I\'ll be right back.\") Staff need to know who is in the room.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 促進剤 conversation.</strong> If labor stalls, the doctor may suggest a 陣痛促進剤 (<em>jintsuu sokushinzai</em>, labor-inducing drug) by IV drip. This requires a signed consent form. Ask: <span lang=\"ja\">「なぜ必要ですか。」</span> (\"Why is it necessary?\")</li>\n      <li><strong>Eat and drink, you too.</strong> Labor can last 20 hours. Hospitals have vending machines and a convenience store. A husband who faints is not helping. Keep a rice ball and water in your bag.</li>\n      <li><strong>Silence between contractions is normal.</strong> Don\'t fill every second with talk. Let her rest in the gaps; be ready when the next one comes.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Presence is the job.</strong> Japanese midwives do not expect the husband to give medical opinions. They expect him to be calm, quiet, and physically helpful: water, ice, towel, back massage, hand to hold.</li>\n      <li><strong>Don\'t leave without saying so.</strong> If you step out, tell the midwife: <span lang=\"ja\">「ちょっと<ruby>出<rp>(</rp><rt>で</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ます。すぐ<ruby>戻<rp>(</rp><rt>もど</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ります。」</span> (\"I\'m stepping out. I\'ll be right back.\") Staff need to know who is in the room.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 促進剤 conversation.</strong> If labor stalls, the doctor may suggest a 陣痛促進剤 (<em>jintsuu sokushinzai</em>, labor-inducing drug) by IV drip. This requires a signed consent form. Ask: <span lang=\"ja\">「なぜ<ruby>必要<rp>(</rp><rt>ひつよう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ですか。」</span> (\"Why is it necessary?\")</li>\n      <li><strong>Eat and drink, you too.</strong> Labor can last 20 hours. Hospitals have vending machines and a convenience store. A husband who faints is not helping. Keep a rice ball and water in your bag.</li>\n      <li><strong>Silence between contractions is normal.</strong> Don\'t fill every second with talk. Let her rest in the gaps; be ready when the next one comes.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(355,303,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(356,304,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(357,305,1,'paragraph',NULL,'The cervix is fully open (<span lang=\"ja\">全開</span>). Your wife is moved to the delivery room (<span lang=\"ja\">分娩室</span>) and onto the delivery table (<span lang=\"ja\">分娩台</span>). From here the instructions come fast and loud. <strong>You do not need to understand every word, you need to recognize six commands</strong>, listed below. Learn these six and you can follow the entire birth.','The cervix is fully open (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>全開<rp>(</rp><rt>ぜんかい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>). Your wife is moved to the delivery room (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>分娩室<rp>（</rp><rt>ぶんべんしつ</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>) and onto the delivery table (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>分娩台<rp>（</rp><rt>ぶんべんだい</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>). From here the instructions come fast and loud. <strong>You do not need to understand every word, you need to recognize six commands</strong>, listed below. Learn these six and you can follow the entire birth.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(358,305,2,'note','The Six Commands of the Delivery Room',NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(359,305,3,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(360,306,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(361,307,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(362,308,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(363,309,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(364,310,1,'scene',NULL,'The final twenty minutes. Doctor, midwife, nurse, husband, wife.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(365,310,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(366,311,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(367,312,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(368,313,1,'culture_note','The Japanese Delivery Room','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Cutting the cord is often offered.</strong> Many Japanese hospitals invite the father to cut the umbilical cord (<span lang=\"ja\">へその緒</span>). If you want to, say so beforehand: <span lang=\"ja\">「へその緒を切りたいです。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>The birth cry matters.</strong> The <span lang=\"ja\">産声</span> (<em>ubugoe</em>, first cry) is emotionally significant in Japan. Staff will comment on how strong it is, this is their way of telling you the baby is breathing well.</li>\n      <li><strong>Skin-to-skin (カンガルーケア).</strong> Most hospitals place the baby on the mother\'s chest immediately. It is called <span lang=\"ja\">カンガルーケア</span> or <span lang=\"ja\">早期母子接触</span>.</li>\n      <li><strong>Photos:</strong> Ask before filming. Many hospitals allow photos after the birth but not during. <span lang=\"ja\">「写真を撮ってもいいですか。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>The placenta (胎盤) comes after.</strong> Do not be alarmed when the staff keep working after the baby is out, delivering the placenta and stitching any tear (<span lang=\"ja\">会陰切開</span>, <em>ein sekkai</em>, episiotomy) takes another 20, 30 minutes. This is normal.</li>\n      <li><strong>Thank everyone.</strong> When it\'s over, say to the whole team: <span lang=\"ja\">「ありがとうございました。お世話になりました。」</span> It will be remembered.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Cutting the cord is often offered.</strong> Many Japanese hospitals invite the father to cut the umbilical cord (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>へその緒<rp>（</rp><rt>へそのお</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>). If you want to, say so beforehand: <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>へその緒<rp>（</rp><rt>へそのお</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby>を<ruby>切<rp>(</rp><rt>き</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>りたいです。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>The birth cry matters.</strong> The <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>産声<rp>(</rp><rt>うぶごえ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> (<em>ubugoe</em>, first cry) is emotionally significant in Japan. Staff will comment on how strong it is, this is their way of telling you the baby is breathing well.</li>\n      <li><strong>Skin-to-skin (カンガルーケア).</strong> Most hospitals place the baby on the mother\'s chest immediately. It is called <span lang=\"ja\">カンガルーケア</span> or <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>早期<rp>(</rp><rt>そうき</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>母子<rp>(</rp><rt>ぼし</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>接触<rp>(</rp><rt>せっしょく</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>.</li>\n      <li><strong>Photos:</strong> Ask before filming. Many hospitals allow photos after the birth but not during. <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>写真<rp>(</rp><rt>しゃしん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>を<ruby>撮<rp>(</rp><rt>と</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>ってもいいですか。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>The placenta (胎盤) comes after.</strong> Do not be alarmed when the staff keep working after the baby is out, delivering the placenta and stitching any tear (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>会陰切開<rp>（</rp><rt>えいんせっかい</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>, <em>ein sekkai</em>, episiotomy) takes another 20, 30 minutes. This is normal.</li>\n      <li><strong>Thank everyone.</strong> When it\'s over, say to the whole team: <span lang=\"ja\">「ありがとうございました。お<ruby>世話<rp>(</rp><rt>せわ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>になりました。」</span> It will be remembered.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(369,314,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(370,315,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(371,316,1,'paragraph',NULL,'The baby is here. Now come the questions every new father asks in the first hour: <em>Is my wife okay? Is the baby okay? Can I see the baby? Can I hold the baby?</em> This chapter also covers photographs, calling family, and arranging visits.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(372,317,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(373,318,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(374,319,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(375,320,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(376,321,1,'scene',NULL,'The husband talks with the nurse and his wife, and calls his mother-in-law.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(377,321,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(378,322,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(379,323,1,'culture_note','The First Day — Japanese Customs','<ul>\n      <li><strong>母子同室 (boshi doushitsu), rooming-in.</strong> Most Japanese maternity hospitals keep mother and baby together from day one, so the mother learns feeding immediately. Some hospitals will take the baby at night if the mother is exhausted, you can ask: <span lang=\"ja\">「今夜だけ預かってもらえますか。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Visiting is restricted.</strong> Japanese hospitals limit visitors strictly, often only the husband and grandparents, in narrow visiting hours, sometimes no children under 12. Check the rules before inviting anyone.</li>\n      <li><strong>お疲れさまでした.</strong> This is the correct thing to say to your wife and to the staff. It means \"you have worked hard\" and is far more natural in Japanese than \"congratulations\" alone.</li>\n      <li><strong>Wash your hands, every single time.</strong> Before touching the baby, always <span lang=\"ja\">手を洗う</span> and use the alcohol dispenser. Staff notice this and it builds trust immediately.</li>\n      <li><strong>The birth certificate clock starts now.</strong> You have <strong>14 days</strong> to register the birth (<span lang=\"ja\">出生届</span>, <em>shusshou todoke</em>) at the city office. The hospital gives you a birth certificate form (<span lang=\"ja\">出生証明書</span>) signed by the doctor. Do not lose it. See Chapter 19.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>母子同室 (boshi doushitsu), rooming-in.</strong> Most Japanese maternity hospitals keep mother and baby together from day one, so the mother learns feeding immediately. Some hospitals will take the baby at night if the mother is exhausted, you can ask: <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>今夜<rp>(</rp><rt>こんや</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>だけ<ruby>預<rp>(</rp><rt>あず</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>かってもらえますか。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Visiting is restricted.</strong> Japanese hospitals limit visitors strictly, often only the husband and grandparents, in narrow visiting hours, sometimes no children under 12. Check the rules before inviting anyone.</li>\n      <li><strong>お疲れさまでした.</strong> This is the correct thing to say to your wife and to the staff. It means \"you have worked hard\" and is far more natural in Japanese than \"congratulations\" alone.</li>\n      <li><strong>Wash your hands, every single time.</strong> Before touching the baby, always <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>手<rp>(</rp><rt>て</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>を<ruby>洗<rp>(</rp><rt>あら</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>う</span> and use the alcohol dispenser. Staff notice this and it builds trust immediately.</li>\n      <li><strong>The birth certificate clock starts now.</strong> You have <strong>14 days</strong> to register the birth (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>出生<rp>(</rp><rt>しゅっしょう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>届<rp>(</rp><rt>とどけ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>shusshou todoke</em>) at the city office. The hospital gives you a birth certificate form (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>出生<rp>(</rp><rt>しゅっしょう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>証明<rp>(</rp><rt>しょうめい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>書<rp>(</rp><rt>しょ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>) signed by the doctor. Do not lose it. See Chapter 19.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(380,324,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(381,325,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(382,326,1,'paragraph',NULL,'In Japan a normal delivery means a hospital stay of about <strong>five days</strong> (a C-section, about a week). That is five days of meals, showers, laundry, Wi-Fi questions, air conditioning, room cleaning, and visitors. This chapter gives you the everyday sentences of hospital life.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(383,327,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(384,328,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(385,329,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(386,330,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(387,331,1,'scene',NULL,'Laundry, room cleaning, quiet hours, and a visitor question, all in one morning.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(388,331,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(389,332,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(390,333,1,'culture_note','Living in a Japanese Hospital','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Silence is the rule.</strong> Japanese wards are extremely quiet. Consider 9 p.m. (消灯, lights out) an absolute boundary. No phone calls in rooms, no loud voices in corridors, ever.</li>\n      <li><strong>Bring 100-yen coins.</strong> Laundry, dryers, some TVs, and lockers all run on coins. Keep a small bag of ¥100 coins in the hospital bag, this is a genuinely useful piece of advice.</li>\n      <li><strong>Hospital food is part of the care.</strong> Maternity hospitals in Japan are famous for excellent food, some serve a celebratory \"お祝い膳\" (<em>oiwai-zen</em>, celebration meal) before discharge. Family meals are usually not included, so eat at the shop or bring food.</li>\n      <li><strong>Visiting is a formality.</strong> Visitors sign in at reception, wear a visitor badge, sanitize hands, and wear a mask. Small children are frequently banned outright. Warn relatives in advance so nobody is turned away at the door.</li>\n      <li><strong>Gifts:</strong> Visitors often bring a small gift (お見舞い, <em>omimai</em>). Flowers are sometimes prohibited in maternity wards (pollen/infection). Sweets or fruit are safer.</li>\n      <li><strong>The husband\'s role.</strong> Bring clean clothes, take dirty laundry home, refill drinks, and, most valuable of all, let her sleep.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Silence is the rule.</strong> Japanese wards are extremely quiet. Consider 9 p.m. (消灯, lights out) an absolute boundary. No phone calls in rooms, no loud voices in corridors, ever.</li>\n      <li><strong>Bring 100-yen coins.</strong> Laundry, dryers, some TVs, and lockers all run on coins. Keep a small bag of ¥100 coins in the hospital bag, this is a genuinely useful piece of advice.</li>\n      <li><strong>Hospital food is part of the care.</strong> Maternity hospitals in Japan are famous for excellent food, some serve a celebratory \"お祝い膳\" (<em>oiwai-zen</em>, celebration meal) before discharge. Family meals are usually not included, so eat at the shop or bring food.</li>\n      <li><strong>Visiting is a formality.</strong> Visitors sign in at reception, wear a visitor badge, sanitize hands, and wear a mask. Small children are frequently banned outright. Warn relatives in advance so nobody is turned away at the door.</li>\n      <li><strong>Gifts:</strong> Visitors often bring a small gift (お見舞い, <em>omimai</em>). Flowers are sometimes prohibited in maternity wards (pollen/infection). Sweets or fruit are safer.</li>\n      <li><strong>The husband\'s role.</strong> Bring clean clothes, take dirty laundry home, refill drinks, and, most valuable of all, let her sleep.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(391,334,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(392,335,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(393,336,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Feeding (<span lang=\"ja\">授乳</span>, <em>junyuu</em>) is taught by the midwife in the first days. She will show holding positions, latching, burping, and how to combine breast milk (<span lang=\"ja\">母乳</span>, <em>bonyuu</em>) with formula (<span lang=\"ja\">ミルク</span>, <em>miruku</em>). Japanese hospitals name the holds precisely, you will hear <span lang=\"ja\">横抱き</span> (cradle), <span lang=\"ja\">縦抱き</span> (upright), <span lang=\"ja\">交差抱き</span> (cross-cradle), <span lang=\"ja\">脇抱き</span> (football hold).','Feeding (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>授乳<rp>(</rp><rt>じゅにゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>junyuu</em>) is taught by the midwife in the first days. She will show holding positions, latching, burping, and how to combine breast milk (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>母乳<rp>(</rp><rt>ぼにゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>bonyuu</em>) with formula (<span lang=\"ja\">ミルク</span>, <em>miruku</em>). Japanese hospitals name the holds precisely, you will hear <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>横抱<rp>(</rp><rt>よこだ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>き</span> (cradle), <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>縦<rp>(</rp><rt>たて</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>抱<rp>(</rp><rt>いだ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>き</span> (upright), <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>交差<rp>(</rp><rt>こうさ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>抱<rp>(</rp><rt>いだ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>き</span> (cross-cradle), <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>脇<rp>(</rp><rt>わき</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>抱<rp>(</rp><rt>いだ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>き</span> (football hold).','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(394,336,2,'note','Two words that confuse everyone','<p><strong>母乳 (bonyuu)</strong> = breast milk. <strong>ミルク (miruku)</strong> = infant <em>formula</em>, <u>not</u> ordinary milk. If a nurse asks 「ミルクにしますか」 she is asking whether to give formula, not cow\'s milk.</p>','<p><strong>母乳 (bonyuu)</strong> = breast milk. <strong>ミルク (miruku)</strong> = infant <em>formula</em>, <u>not</u> ordinary milk. If a nurse asks 「ミルクにしますか」 she is asking whether to give formula, not cow\'s milk.</p>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(395,337,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(396,338,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(397,339,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(398,340,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(399,341,1,'scene',NULL,'Day three. The baby cries constantly; the mother is worried and exhausted.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(400,341,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(401,342,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(402,343,1,'culture_note','Feeding in Japan','<ul>\n      <li><strong>母乳 is strongly encouraged.</strong> Japanese hospitals push breastfeeding hard, and some mothers feel pressure and guilt if milk is slow. If your wife is struggling, say clearly: <span lang=\"ja\">「母乳が足りないので、ミルクを足したいです。」</span> Formula is not failure.</li>\n      <li><strong>授乳室 (junyuushitsu).</strong> Nursing rooms exist in almost every Japanese department store, station, and mall, usually clean, free, with hot water for formula. Look for the sign <span lang=\"ja\">授乳室</span> or <span lang=\"ja\">ベビールーム</span>.</li>\n      <li><strong>Fathers can do everything except breastfeed.</strong> Taking the night formula feed is the single most valuable thing you can do this week. Ask the midwife to teach you: <span lang=\"ja\">「ミルクの作り方を教えてください。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Breast massage (母乳マッサージ) is a real service.</strong> Japanese midwives are trained in it and it is standard postpartum care. Encourage your wife to accept it, it prevents 乳腺炎 (<em>nyuusen\'en</em>, mastitis).</li>\n      <li><strong>Watch for mastitis.</strong> If a breast becomes hot, hard, red, and she has a fever, tell the nurse immediately: <span lang=\"ja\">「おっぱいが熱くて、熱があります。」</span> This needs treatment.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>母乳 is strongly encouraged.</strong> Japanese hospitals push breastfeeding hard, and some mothers feel pressure and guilt if milk is slow. If your wife is struggling, say clearly: <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>母乳<rp>(</rp><rt>ぼにゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>が<ruby>足<rp>(</rp><rt>た</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>りないので、ミルクを<ruby>足<rp>(</rp><rt>た</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>したいです。」</span> Formula is not failure.</li>\n      <li><strong>授乳室 (junyuushitsu).</strong> Nursing rooms exist in almost every Japanese department store, station, and mall, usually clean, free, with hot water for formula. Look for the sign <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>授乳<rp>(</rp><rt>じゅにゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>室<rp>(</rp><rt>しつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> or <span lang=\"ja\">ベビールーム</span>.</li>\n      <li><strong>Fathers can do everything except breastfeed.</strong> Taking the night formula feed is the single most valuable thing you can do this week. Ask the midwife to teach you: <span lang=\"ja\">「ミルクの<ruby>作<rp>(</rp><rt>つく</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>り<ruby>方<rp>(</rp><rt>かた</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>を<ruby>教<rp>(</rp><rt>おし</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>えてください。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Breast massage (母乳マッサージ) is a real service.</strong> Japanese midwives are trained in it and it is standard postpartum care. Encourage your wife to accept it, it prevents 乳腺炎 (<em>nyuusen\'en</em>, mastitis).</li>\n      <li><strong>Watch for mastitis.</strong> If a breast becomes hot, hard, red, and she has a fever, tell the nurse immediately: <span lang=\"ja\">「おっぱいが<ruby>熱<rp>(</rp><rt>あつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>くて、<ruby>熱<rp>(</rp><rt>ねつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>があります。」</span> This needs treatment.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(403,344,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(404,345,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(405,346,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Before discharge, the hospital teaches you baby care: diaper changes, the baby bath (<span lang=\"ja\">沐浴</span>, <em>mokuyoku</em>), umbilical cord care, sleeping, and what to do about fever and medicine. Japanese hospitals run a formal <strong>沐浴指導</strong> (<em>mokuyoku shidou</em>, bathing class), fathers are welcome and should attend.','Before discharge, the hospital teaches you baby care: diaper changes, the baby bath (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>沐浴<rp>（</rp><rt>もくよく</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby></span>, <em>mokuyoku</em>), umbilical cord care, sleeping, and what to do about fever and medicine. Japanese hospitals run a formal <strong>沐浴指導</strong> (<em>mokuyoku shidou</em>, bathing class), fathers are welcome and should attend.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(406,347,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(407,348,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(408,349,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(409,350,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(410,351,1,'scene',NULL,'A nurse teaches the father to bathe the baby, the famous 沐浴指導.','A nurse teaches the father to bathe the baby, the famous 沐浴指導.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(411,351,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(412,352,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(413,353,1,'culture_note','Baby Care the Japanese Way','<ul>\n      <li><strong>沐浴指導 is for fathers.</strong> Japanese hospitals expect fathers to attend the bathing class, and in many families bathing the baby becomes the father\'s permanent job. Volunteer for it.</li>\n      <li><strong>Always on the back.</strong> Japanese guidance is strict: babies sleep <span lang=\"ja\">あお向け</span> (on their back), on a firm mattress, with no pillow and no soft toys. This is SIDS prevention (乳幼児突然死症候群).</li>\n      <li><strong>37.5°C is the magic number.</strong> For a newborn, 37.5 degrees or higher means <em>call the hospital now</em>, not tomorrow morning. Keep a digital thermometer at home.</li>\n      <li><strong>Never medicate a newborn on your own.</strong> No adult medicine, no fever reducer, no herbal remedy without the doctor. This is stressed heavily in Japan.</li>\n      <li><strong>The dried umbilical cord is kept.</strong> Japanese hospitals traditionally give the family a small wooden box (<span lang=\"ja\">へその緒入れ</span>) containing the dried cord stump. It\'s a keepsake, not a mistake, don\'t throw it away.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>沐浴指導 is for fathers.</strong> Japanese hospitals expect fathers to attend the bathing class, and in many families bathing the baby becomes the father\'s permanent job. Volunteer for it.</li>\n      <li><strong>Always on the back.</strong> Japanese guidance is strict: babies sleep <span lang=\"ja\">あお<ruby>向<rp>(</rp><rt>む</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>け</span> (on their back), on a firm mattress, with no pillow and no soft toys. This is SIDS prevention (乳幼児突然死症候群).</li>\n      <li><strong>37.5°C is the magic number.</strong> For a newborn, 37.5 degrees or higher means <em>call the hospital now</em>, not tomorrow morning. Keep a digital thermometer at home.</li>\n      <li><strong>Never medicate a newborn on your own.</strong> No adult medicine, no fever reducer, no herbal remedy without the doctor. This is stressed heavily in Japan.</li>\n      <li><strong>The dried umbilical cord is kept.</strong> Japanese hospitals traditionally give the family a small wooden box (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>へその緒<rp>（</rp><rt>へそのお</rt><rp>）</rp></ruby><ruby>入<rp>(</rp><rt>い</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>れ</span>) containing the dried cord stump. It\'s a keepsake, not a mistake, don\'t throw it away.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(414,354,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(415,355,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(416,356,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Before discharge, the doctor and the pediatrician (<span lang=\"ja\">小児科の先生</span>) explain the baby\'s health, the mother\'s recovery, medicines to take home, the vaccination schedule (<span lang=\"ja\">予防接種</span>, <em>yobou sesshu</em>), and the next appointments. Bring a notebook, and don\'t be afraid to ask for a slower repeat.','Before discharge, the doctor and the pediatrician (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>小児科<rp>(</rp><rt>しょうにか</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>の<ruby>先生<rp>(</rp><rt>せんせい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>) explain the baby\'s health, the mother\'s recovery, medicines to take home, the vaccination schedule (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>予防<rp>(</rp><rt>よぼう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>接種<rp>(</rp><rt>せっしゅ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>yobou sesshu</em>), and the next appointments. Bring a notebook, and don\'t be afraid to ask for a slower repeat.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(417,357,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(418,358,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(419,359,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(420,360,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(421,361,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(422,362,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(423,363,1,'culture_note','Understanding Japanese Medical Explanations','<ul>\n      <li><strong>異常なし (ijou nashi) = \"no abnormality.\"</strong> This is the phrase you want to hear. It means everything is normal.</li>\n      <li><strong>Vaccinations are free but not automatic.</strong> Routine vaccines (定期接種) are paid by your city. The city mails you a set of forms (予診票, <em>yoshinhyou</em>); you book the appointments yourself at a pediatric clinic. Nobody chases you, it is your responsibility.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 母子手帳 is the vaccination record.</strong> Every shot gets stamped in the handbook. Schools and clinics will ask for it for years. Never lose it; photograph the pages as backup.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ask for written notes.</strong> Japanese doctors are used to writing things down. <span lang=\"ja\">「紙に書いてもらえますか。」</span> is a completely normal request and solves most listening problems.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ask about side effects.</strong> <span lang=\"ja\">副作用 (fukusayou)</span>, pharmacists in Japan explain them thoroughly and give you a printed sheet with the medicine.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>異常なし (ijou nashi) = \"no abnormality.\"</strong> This is the phrase you want to hear. It means everything is normal.</li>\n      <li><strong>Vaccinations are free but not automatic.</strong> Routine vaccines (定期接種) are paid by your city. The city mails you a set of forms (予診票, <em>yoshinhyou</em>); you book the appointments yourself at a pediatric clinic. Nobody chases you, it is your responsibility.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 母子手帳 is the vaccination record.</strong> Every shot gets stamped in the handbook. Schools and clinics will ask for it for years. Never lose it; photograph the pages as backup.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ask for written notes.</strong> Japanese doctors are used to writing things down. <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>紙<rp>(</rp><rt>かみ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>に<ruby>書<rp>(</rp><rt>か</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>いてもらえますか。」</span> is a completely normal request and solves most listening problems.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ask about side effects.</strong> <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>副作用<rp>(</rp><rt>ふくさよう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby> (fukusayou)</span>, pharmacists in Japan explain them thoroughly and give you a printed sheet with the medicine.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(424,364,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(425,365,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(426,366,1,'paragraph',NULL,'In Japan the hospital does not usually give you the medicine. It gives you a <strong>prescription</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">処方箋</span>, <em>shohousen</em>), which you take to a pharmacy (<span lang=\"ja\">調剤薬局</span>, <em>chouzai yakkyoku</em>), normally right next door. You will also need a drugstore (<span lang=\"ja\">ドラッグストア</span>) for diapers, baby soap, formula, and a thermometer.','In Japan the hospital does not usually give you the medicine. It gives you a <strong>prescription</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>処方箋<rp>(</rp><rt>しょほうせん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>shohousen</em>), which you take to a pharmacy (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>調剤<rp>(</rp><rt>ちょうざい</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>薬局<rp>(</rp><rt>やっきょく</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>chouzai yakkyoku</em>), normally right next door. You will also need a drugstore (<span lang=\"ja\">ドラッグストア</span>) for diapers, baby soap, formula, and a thermometer.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(427,367,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(428,368,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(429,369,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(430,370,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(431,371,1,'scene',NULL,'A complete drugstore run before discharge, formula, diapers, wipes, and paying.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(432,371,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(433,372,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(434,373,1,'culture_note','Japanese Pharmacies','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Get an お薬手帳.</strong> This free booklet records every medicine you have ever been prescribed. Pharmacists check it for dangerous interactions, and showing it can lower your fee. Get one for your wife and one for the baby.</li>\n      <li><strong>The prescription expires.</strong> A Japanese 処方箋 is valid for only <strong>4 days</strong> including the day it was issued. Do not put it in a drawer.</li>\n      <li><strong>Pharmacists really do explain.</strong> They will tell you dose, timing, and side effects, and hand you a printed sheet. If you don\'t understand, ask: <span lang=\"ja\">「ゆっくりお願いします。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Drugstores are cheaper than hospital shops.</strong> Chains like Matsumoto Kiyoshi, Sundrug, and Welcia sell diapers and formula far cheaper. Bulk diapers are cheapest online or at Akachan Honpo / Nishimatsuya (baby superstores).</li>\n      <li><strong>液体ミルク (liquid formula)</strong> is a relatively new and genuinely useful product in Japan, no hot water, no mixing. Perfect for night feeds and emergencies. Keep some at home.</li>\n      <li><strong>お大事に (odaiji ni)</strong> is what staff say as you leave. You don\'t need to reply with more than <span lang=\"ja\">「ありがとうございます。」</span></li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>Get an お薬手帳.</strong> This free booklet records every medicine you have ever been prescribed. Pharmacists check it for dangerous interactions, and showing it can lower your fee. Get one for your wife and one for the baby.</li>\n      <li><strong>The prescription expires.</strong> A Japanese 処方箋 is valid for only <strong>4 days</strong> including the day it was issued. Do not put it in a drawer.</li>\n      <li><strong>Pharmacists really do explain.</strong> They will tell you dose, timing, and side effects, and hand you a printed sheet. If you don\'t understand, ask: <span lang=\"ja\">「ゆっくりお<ruby>願<rp>(</rp><rt>ねが</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>いします。」</span></li>\n      <li><strong>Drugstores are cheaper than hospital shops.</strong> Chains like Matsumoto Kiyoshi, Sundrug, and Welcia sell diapers and formula far cheaper. Bulk diapers are cheapest online or at Akachan Honpo / Nishimatsuya (baby superstores).</li>\n      <li><strong>液体ミルク (liquid formula)</strong> is a relatively new and genuinely useful product in Japan, no hot water, no mixing. Perfect for night feeds and emergencies. Keep some at home.</li>\n      <li><strong>お大事に (odaiji ni)</strong> is what staff say as you leave. You don\'t need to reply with more than <span lang=\"ja\">「ありがとうございます。」</span></li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(435,374,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(436,375,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(437,376,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Discharge day (<span lang=\"ja\">退院</span>, <em>taiin</em>). You settle the bill, use the childbirth lump-sum grant, book the one-month checkup, and take your family home. The key financial term: <strong>出産育児一時金</strong> (<em>shussan ikuji ichijikin</em>), a government lump-sum grant (currently ¥500,000) that is usually paid <em>directly to the hospital</em>, so you only pay the difference.','Discharge day (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>退院<rp>(</rp><rt>たいいん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>, <em>taiin</em>). You settle the bill, use the childbirth lump-sum grant, book the one-month checkup, and take your family home. The key financial term: <strong>出産育児一時金</strong> (<em>shussan ikuji ichijikin</em>), a government lump-sum grant (currently ¥500,000) that is usually paid <em>directly to the hospital</em>, so you only pay the difference.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(438,377,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(439,378,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(440,379,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(441,380,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(442,381,1,'scene',NULL,'Discharge guidance (退院指導), the last documents, and goodbye to the staff.','Discharge guidance (退院指導), the last documents, and goodbye to the staff.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(443,381,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(444,382,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(445,383,1,'culture_note','Money & Paperwork at Discharge','<ul>\n      <li><strong>出産育児一時金, the ¥500,000 grant.</strong> Under the \"direct payment system\" (直接支払制度), the health insurer pays the hospital directly; you pay only the excess. Sign up for this <em>during pregnancy</em> at the hospital, or you\'ll have to front the whole amount and claim it back.</li>\n      <li><strong>Normal birth is not covered by insurance.</strong> Childbirth is not an \"illness,\" so the 30% insurance rule does not apply, the grant is the mechanism instead. A C-section <em>is</em> covered by insurance, and may also trigger 高額療養費 (high-cost medical expense reimbursement).</li>\n      <li><strong>Keep every receipt.</strong> Medical expenses over ¥100,000 in a year can be deducted from tax (医療費控除). Birth costs usually qualify. Keep receipts including taxi fares to the hospital on the day of labor.</li>\n      <li><strong>Some hospitals are cash only.</strong> Confirm in advance: <span lang=\"ja\">「カードは使えますか。」</span> If not, you\'ll need to bring ¥100,000+ in cash on discharge day.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 14-day clock.</strong> 出生届 (birth registration) must be filed at the city office within 14 days. Bring: the 出生証明書 from the hospital, the 母子手帳, your 印鑑, and your residence card. Do this together with the health insurance registration and the child allowance (児童手当) application, one trip, three forms.</li>\n      <li><strong>Child car seat is legally required</strong> in Japan for children under 6. Hospitals will ask. Have it installed before discharge day.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>出産育児一時金, the ¥500,000 grant.</strong> Under the \"direct payment system\" (直接支払制度), the health insurer pays the hospital directly; you pay only the excess. Sign up for this <em>during pregnancy</em> at the hospital, or you\'ll have to front the whole amount and claim it back.</li>\n      <li><strong>Normal birth is not covered by insurance.</strong> Childbirth is not an \"illness,\" so the 30% insurance rule does not apply, the grant is the mechanism instead. A C-section <em>is</em> covered by insurance, and may also trigger 高額療養費 (high-cost medical expense reimbursement).</li>\n      <li><strong>Keep every receipt.</strong> Medical expenses over ¥100,000 in a year can be deducted from tax (医療費控除). Birth costs usually qualify. Keep receipts including taxi fares to the hospital on the day of labor.</li>\n      <li><strong>Some hospitals are cash only.</strong> Confirm in advance: <span lang=\"ja\">「カードは<ruby>使<rp>(</rp><rt>つか</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>えますか。」</span> If not, you\'ll need to bring ¥100,000+ in cash on discharge day.</li>\n      <li><strong>The 14-day clock.</strong> 出生届 (birth registration) must be filed at the city office within 14 days. Bring: the 出生証明書 from the hospital, the 母子手帳, your 印鑑, and your residence card. Do this together with the health insurance registration and the child allowance (児童手当) application, one trip, three forms.</li>\n      <li><strong>Child car seat is legally required</strong> in Japan for children under 6. Hospitals will ask. Have it installed before discharge day.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(446,384,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(447,385,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(448,386,1,'paragraph',NULL,'The <span lang=\"ja\">一か月健診</span> is the first big milestone after going home. Both mother and baby are examined: the baby\'s weight, height, head circumference, reflexes; the mother\'s uterus, stitches, and mental health. Bring the 母子手帳, the doctor writes the results in it.','The <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>一<rp>(</rp><rt>いち</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>か<ruby>月<rp>(</rp><rt>げつ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>健<rp>(</rp><rt>けん</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby><ruby>診<rp>(</rp><rt>み</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span> is the first big milestone after going home. Both mother and baby are examined: the baby\'s weight, height, head circumference, reflexes; the mother\'s uterus, stitches, and mental health. Bring the 母子手帳, the doctor writes the results in it.','2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(449,387,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(450,388,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:35','2026-07-12 20:17:35'),(451,389,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(452,390,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(453,391,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(454,392,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(455,393,1,'culture_note','Postnatal Support in Japan','<ul>\n      <li><strong>保健センター (hoken sentaa), the public health center.</strong> Every municipality has one. A 保健師 (public health nurse) will visit your home free of charge in the first months to weigh the baby and check on the mother. Say yes to this visit, it is genuinely useful and it is your right as a resident.</li>\n      <li><strong>産後うつ (postnatal depression) is taken seriously now.</strong> The one-month checkup includes a mood questionnaire. Encourage your wife to answer honestly, not politely. Foreign mothers in Japan are at higher risk because of isolation and language.</li>\n      <li><strong>Vaccination schedules are dense.</strong> Japanese babies receive many vaccines starting at 2 months, often 4, 6 injections in a single visit (同時接種). This is normal and considered safe here.</li>\n      <li><strong>The growth curve (成長曲線).</strong> The 母子手帳 has printed growth graphs. The doctor plots your baby on them at every checkup. Ask to see the page, it\'s a great way to understand the explanation even with limited Japanese.</li>\n      <li><strong>Next checkups:</strong> 3, 4 months, 6, 7 months, 9, 10 months, 1 year, 1.5 years, 3 years. Most are free at the city\'s designated clinics.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>保健センター (hoken sentaa), the public health center.</strong> Every municipality has one. A 保健師 (public health nurse) will visit your home free of charge in the first months to weigh the baby and check on the mother. Say yes to this visit, it is genuinely useful and it is your right as a resident.</li>\n      <li><strong>産後うつ (postnatal depression) is taken seriously now.</strong> The one-month checkup includes a mood questionnaire. Encourage your wife to answer honestly, not politely. Foreign mothers in Japan are at higher risk because of isolation and language.</li>\n      <li><strong>Vaccination schedules are dense.</strong> Japanese babies receive many vaccines starting at 2 months, often 4, 6 injections in a single visit (同時接種). This is normal and considered safe here.</li>\n      <li><strong>The growth curve (成長曲線).</strong> The 母子手帳 has printed growth graphs. The doctor plots your baby on them at every checkup. Ask to see the page, it\'s a great way to understand the explanation even with limited Japanese.</li>\n      <li><strong>Next checkups:</strong> 3, 4 months, 6, 7 months, 9, 10 months, 1 year, 1.5 years, 3 years. Most are free at the city\'s designated clinics.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(456,394,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(457,395,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(458,396,1,'paragraph',NULL,'This is the chapter you hope never to use. Learn it anyway. It covers a newborn\'s fever, heavy bleeding in the mother, a baby refusing milk, breathing difficulty, and how to call an ambulance or a night clinic. <strong>Read section 18.3 out loud until you can say it without looking.</strong>',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(459,396,2,'note','Emergency numbers — put these in your phone tonight','<ul>\n      <li><strong>119</strong>, Fire &amp; ambulance (救急車). Free. Say: <span lang=\"ja\">救急です。</span> (<em>Kyuukyuu desu.</em>)</li>\n      <li><strong>#8000</strong>, Nationwide pediatric after-hours phone advice (子ども医療電話相談). Nurses/doctors advise you whether to go to hospital tonight. Japanese only in most areas, but a lifeline.</li>\n      <li><strong>#7119</strong>, Emergency consultation line (available in many areas): \"Should I call an ambulance?\"</li>\n      <li><strong>Your hospital\'s night number</strong>, write it here and stick it on the fridge.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>119</strong>, Fire &amp; ambulance (救急車). Free. Say: <span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>救急<rp>(</rp><rt>きゅうきゅう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>です。</span> (<em>Kyuukyuu desu.</em>)</li>\n      <li><strong>#8000</strong>, Nationwide pediatric after-hours phone advice (子ども医療電話相談). Nurses/doctors advise you whether to go to hospital tonight. Japanese only in most areas, but a lifeline.</li>\n      <li><strong>#7119</strong>, Emergency consultation line (available in many areas): \"Should I call an ambulance?\"</li>\n      <li><strong>Your hospital\'s night number</strong>, write it here and stick it on the fridge.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(460,397,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(461,398,1,'scene',NULL,'Memorize these. In a real emergency, one clear sentence is worth more than a paragraph.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(462,398,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(463,399,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(464,400,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(465,401,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(466,402,1,'culture_note','Emergencies in Japan — What You Must Know','<ul>\n      <li><strong>A fever in a baby under 3 months is always an emergency.</strong> 38°C or above in a newborn = go to hospital, at any hour. Do not \"wait until morning.\"</li>\n      <li><strong>Ambulances are free but not taxis.</strong> Japanese ambulances cost nothing, but calling one for a minor problem is frowned upon and slows the system. Use #7119 or #8000 if you\'re unsure.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ambulances ask which hospital.</strong> The crew will ask 「かかりつけの病院はありますか」 (\"Do you have a regular hospital?\"). Know the name of your clinic and say it clearly. Have it written down in Japanese in your wallet.</li>\n      <li><strong>Danger signs in a newborn, go immediately:</strong> fever 38°C+, limp/unresponsive (ぐったり), blue lips (唇が青い), fast or labored breathing, refusing all feeds, convulsions (けいれん), a bulging soft spot, no wet diaper for 12 hours.</li>\n      <li><strong>Danger signs in the mother:</strong> soaking a pad in under an hour, large clots, fever with chills, severe headache with blurred vision (可能性: postpartum preeclampsia), a hot painful red breast, calf pain and swelling, or thoughts of harming herself or the baby.</li>\n      <li><strong>Prepare a \"go card.\"</strong> Write in Japanese: your name, address, phone, your wife\'s name, the hospital name, allergies, and blood types. Keep it in your wallet. In a panic, hand over the card.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>A fever in a baby under 3 months is always an emergency.</strong> 38°C or above in a newborn = go to hospital, at any hour. Do not \"wait until morning.\"</li>\n      <li><strong>Ambulances are free but not taxis.</strong> Japanese ambulances cost nothing, but calling one for a minor problem is frowned upon and slows the system. Use #7119 or #8000 if you\'re unsure.</li>\n      <li><strong>Ambulances ask which hospital.</strong> The crew will ask 「かかりつけの病院はありますか」 (\"Do you have a regular hospital?\"). Know the name of your clinic and say it clearly. Have it written down in Japanese in your wallet.</li>\n      <li><strong>Danger signs in a newborn, go immediately:</strong> fever 38°C+, limp/unresponsive (ぐったり), blue lips (唇が青い), fast or labored breathing, refusing all feeds, convulsions (けいれん), a bulging soft spot, no wet diaper for 12 hours.</li>\n      <li><strong>Danger signs in the mother:</strong> soaking a pad in under an hour, large clots, fever with chills, severe headache with blurred vision (可能性: postpartum preeclampsia), a hot painful red breast, calf pain and swelling, or thoughts of harming herself or the baby.</li>\n      <li><strong>Prepare a \"go card.\"</strong> Write in Japanese: your name, address, phone, your wife\'s name, the hospital name, allergies, and blood types. Keep it in your wallet. In a panic, hand over the card.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(467,403,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(468,404,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(469,405,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Life with a newborn means the convenience store at 3 a.m., taxis with a baby, the drugstore, and, most importantly, the <strong>city office</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\">市役所</span>), where you must register the birth within 14 days and claim your benefits. This chapter covers all of it, plus nursery school and parking.','Life with a newborn means the convenience store at 3 a.m., taxis with a baby, the drugstore, and, most importantly, the <strong>city office</strong> (<span lang=\"ja\"><ruby>市役所<rp>(</rp><rt>しやくしょ</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby></span>), where you must register the birth within 14 days and claim your benefits. This chapter covers all of it, plus nursery school and parking.','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(470,406,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(471,407,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(472,408,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(473,409,1,'scene',NULL,'The single most important errand of the first two weeks: registering the birth and claiming benefits.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(474,409,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(475,410,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(476,411,1,'culture_note','Daily Life With a Baby in Japan','<ul>\n      <li><strong>The 14-day birth registration is a hard deadline.</strong> Go to the 市役所 with: 出生証明書 (from the hospital), 母子手帳, your 在留カード, your 印鑑, and your bankbook. Do all four procedures in one visit, birth registration, child allowance, infant medical certificate, health insurance.</li>\n      <li><strong>乳幼児医療証, free healthcare for the baby.</strong> Most municipalities make medical care free (or nearly) for infants. Carry this card with the insurance card whenever you go to a clinic.</li>\n      <li><strong>Foreign names go in katakana.</strong> On the birth registration, a foreign child\'s name is written in katakana (and romaji). Decide the spelling in advance, it becomes official.</li>\n      <li><strong>Also register the birth with your own embassy</strong> and apply for the child\'s passport and (if applicable) a Japanese residence status. The hospital will not remind you.</li>\n      <li><strong>保育園 (nursery) is competitive.</strong> In cities, applications open in the autumn for the following April, and demand far exceeds supply (待機児童 problem). Apply early, even if the baby is only a few months old.</li>\n      <li><strong>Baby rooms are everywhere.</strong> Department stores, malls, train stations, and even highway rest stops have <span lang=\"ja\">ベビールーム</span> with changing tables, hot water for formula, and private nursing booths. They are free and clean. Japan is genuinely excellent at this.</li>\n    </ul>','<ul>\n      <li><strong>The 14-day birth registration is a hard deadline.</strong> Go to the 市役所 with: 出生証明書 (from the hospital), 母子手帳, your 在留カード, your 印鑑, and your bankbook. Do all four procedures in one visit, birth registration, child allowance, infant medical certificate, health insurance.</li>\n      <li><strong>乳幼児医療証, free healthcare for the baby.</strong> Most municipalities make medical care free (or nearly) for infants. Carry this card with the insurance card whenever you go to a clinic.</li>\n      <li><strong>Foreign names go in katakana.</strong> On the birth registration, a foreign child\'s name is written in katakana (and romaji). Decide the spelling in advance, it becomes official.</li>\n      <li><strong>Also register the birth with your own embassy</strong> and apply for the child\'s passport and (if applicable) a Japanese residence status. The hospital will not remind you.</li>\n      <li><strong>保育園 (nursery) is competitive.</strong> In cities, applications open in the autumn for the following April, and demand far exceeds supply (待機児童 problem). Apply early, even if the baby is only a few months old.</li>\n      <li><strong>Baby rooms are everywhere.</strong> Department stores, malls, train stations, and even highway rest stops have <span lang=\"ja\">ベビールーム</span> with changing tables, hot water for formula, and private nursing booths. They are free and clean. Japan is genuinely excellent at this.</li>\n    </ul>','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(477,412,1,'vocab',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(478,413,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(479,414,1,'paragraph',NULL,'Over <strong>500 phrases</strong>, grouped by situation. This is the chapter to keep open on your phone in the hospital corridor. Everything is in polite です・ます form unless marked, so you can say any of it to any member of staff.','Over <strong>500 phrases</strong>, grouped by situation. This is the chapter to keep open on your phone in the hospital corridor. Everything is in polite です・ます form unless marked, so you can say any of it to any member of staff.','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(480,414,2,'paragraph',NULL,'<strong>The five phrases that matter most:</strong> if you learn nothing else, learn these.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(481,414,3,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(482,415,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(483,416,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(484,417,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(485,418,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(486,419,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(487,420,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(488,421,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(489,422,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(490,423,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(491,424,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(492,425,1,'scene',NULL,'You will HEAR these. You don\'t need to say them, you need to recognize them instantly.',NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(493,425,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(494,426,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(495,427,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(496,428,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(497,429,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(498,430,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(499,431,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(500,432,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(501,433,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(502,434,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(503,435,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(504,436,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(505,437,1,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(506,438,1,'note','You are going to be fine','<p>You will not understand everything that is said to you in that hospital. You do not need to. The nurses and midwives of Japan are extraordinarily kind, and they have guided thousands of frightened, exhausted fathers who spoke less Japanese than you do. Say <span lang=\"ja\">「すみません」</span>, say <span lang=\"ja\">「お願いします」</span>, hold your wife\'s hand, and let them lead.</p>\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0\"><strong>そして、赤ちゃんが生まれたら, </strong> <span lang=\"ja\">「本当にありがとうございました。」</span> <em>Soshite, akachan ga umaretara, hontou ni arigatou gozaimashita.</em> And when the baby is born, thank you, from the bottom of my heart.</p>','<p>You will not understand everything that is said to you in that hospital. You do not need to. The nurses and midwives of Japan are extraordinarily kind, and they have guided thousands of frightened, exhausted fathers who spoke less Japanese than you do. Say <span lang=\"ja\">「すみません」</span>, say <span lang=\"ja\">「お<ruby>願<rp>(</rp><rt>ねが</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>いします」</span>, hold your wife\'s hand, and let them lead.</p>\n    <p style=\"margin-bottom:0\"><strong>そして、赤ちゃんが生まれたら, </strong> <span lang=\"ja\">「<ruby>本当<rp>(</rp><rt>ほんとう</rt><rp>)</rp></ruby>にありがとうございました。」</span> <em>Soshite, akachan ga umaretara, hontou ni arigatou gozaimashita.</em> And when the baby is born, thank you, from the bottom of my heart.</p>','2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36'),(507,438,2,'dialogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-07-12 20:17:36','2026-07-12 20:17:36');
